<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="224" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,638,194,713]" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,327,348]" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name refers to its similarity to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,229,353,375]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rileyi">
<emphasis box="[151,229,353,375]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">B. rileyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="224" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,638,194,713]" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,289,380,401]" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species is superficially very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[259,342,406,428]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rileyi">
<emphasis box="[259,342,406,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">B. rileyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is therefore not figured separately; in fact, before I examined the 
<collectingRegion box="[581,638,432,453]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">Texas</collectingRegion>
specimens and only saw the photograph (
<figureCitation box="[564,623,458,479]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[175,215,864,883]" captionTargetBox="[200,1123,204,840]" captionTargetId="figure-438@1.[151,1171,183,866]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–2. Brachys species, dorsal view. 1) B. rileyi; 2) B. barri." pageId="3" pageNumber="224">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), I thought it was conspecific. 
<taxonomicName box="[449,638,484,506]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="consimilis">
<emphasis box="[449,638,484,506]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">Brachys consimilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[283,366,510,532]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rileyi">
<emphasis box="[283,366,510,532]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">B. rileyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most obviously in having incomplete lateral carinae on the elytra; additionally, in 
<taxonomicName box="[222,345,562,584]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Brachys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="consimilis">
<emphasis box="[222,345,562,584]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="224">B. consimilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the elytra are darker in coloration with two weak ridges on the disc and have separately rounded apices, the pronotum is reddish coppery and has the basal, transverse depression interrupted at the middle, and the head has dorsal, rounded protuberances.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
